\begin_layout Section
Vorticity deposition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The propagation of vortex rings as well as the evolution of interfacial
 mixing between two fluids is driven by vorticity and can be described by
 the vorticity transport equation for a compressible fluid.
 Temporarily omitting consideration of multiple fluid species, consider
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\pdv{\vec{\omega}}{t}+\curl(\vec{\omega}\cross\vec{u})=\frac{1}{\rho^{2}}(\grad{\rho}\cross\grad{p})+\curl(\frac{1}{\rho}\div{\vec{\tau}})
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}$
\end_inset

 is the velocity, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\omega}=\curl\vec{u}$
\end_inset

 is the vorticity, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 are the bulk density and pressure, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\tau}$
\end_inset

 is the viscous stress tensor.
 In shock-driven mixing, the baroclinic production term 
\begin_inset Formula $\grad{\rho}\cross\grad{p}$
\end_inset

 dominates, while in vortex-driven flows, the vortex stretching and vorticity
 diffusion terms 
\begin_inset Formula $\curl(\vec{\omega}\cross\vec{u})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\curl(\frac{1}{\rho}\div{\vec{\tau}})$
\end_inset

 drive the formation, evolution, and breakdown of the vortical core.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Richtmyer-Meshkov instability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This work is fundamentally driven by the need to characterize and predict
 the behavior of shock-accelerated inhomogeneous fluids, an effort which
 stretches back to the 1960s with pioneering theoretical predictions by
 Richtmyer and experimental confirmation by Meshkov 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Richtmyer1960,Meshkov1972"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The canonical initial condition under consideration consists of two stratified
 fluids of different densities, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{2}$
\end_inset

, which meet at a corrugated interface.
 Notably, many of the resultant phenomena are shared with the Rayleigh-Taylor
 instability, which can be viewed as a continuously-accelerated cousin of
 the impulsively-accelerated Richtmyer-Meshkov instability.
 A thorough review of recent investigation into both instabilities was conducted
 by Zhou 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Zhou2017a,Zhou2017b"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In both cases, vorticity is deposited at the interface by baroclinicity.
 
\emph on
i.e.

\emph default
 misalignment between the interfacial density gradient and the pressure
 gradient.
 A linearized model of vorticity deposition allows for prediction of post-shock
 interface amplitude growth rates from initial conditions via algebraic
 gas dynamics, namely
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\dv{\eta}{t}=k\varDelta\!VA\,\eta_{0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the sinusoidal perturbation's amplitude and wavenumber are given by
 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, the shock velocity jump by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta\!V$
\end_inset

, and the interfacial Atwood number by 
\begin_inset Formula $A\equiv(\rho_{2}-\rho_{1})/(\rho_{2}+\rho_{1})$
\end_inset

.
 Given that the deposition process occurs as the shock wave is sweeping
 through the interface, there is some ongoing debate as to the suitability
 of the pre-shock 
\emph on
vs.
 
\emph default
post-shock values of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{0}$
\end_inset

, but fairly good agreement is found for most cases by taking the average
 
\begin_inset Formula $(A^{-}\eta_{0}^{-}+A^{+}\eta_{0}^{+})/2$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $^{-}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $^{+}$
\end_inset

 indicating pre- and post-shock conditions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Vandenboomgaerde1998"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In Meshkov's experiments, the initial shape of the interfacial perturbations
 was enforced by a thin nitrocellulose membrane , but the fragmentation
 of this membrane saps the strength of the shock wave and disturbs the post-shoc
k evolution of the interface.
 Additionally, the presence of a solid membrane presents severe difficulties
 for quantitative flow visualization techniques.
 As a result, subsequent workers have adopted a variety of membrane-free
 interfaces involving oscillating pistons, retractable corrugated sheets,
 vibrating walls, gas curtains, 
\emph on
etc.

\emph default
 
