\begin_layout Standard
For numerical models where the conserved scalar and vector fields are known
 throughout the domain, the geometric parameters of the vortex arise straightfor
wardly from the first and second areal moments of vorticity.
 Each of these moments is normalized by the total circulation.
 Following Saffman 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Saffman1970"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and integrating in the local neighborhood of the vortex in axisymmetric
 cylindrical coordinates,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\Gamma & =\iint\omega\dd{r}\dd{z}\label{eq:Gamma_vortex}\\
R & =\frac{1}{\Gamma}\iint\omega r\dd{r}\dd{z}\\
R_{2}^{2} & =\frac{1}{\Gamma}\iint\omega r^{2}\dd{r}\dd{z}\\
z_{c} & =\frac{1}{\Gamma}\iint\omega z\dd{r}\dd{z}\label{eq:z_vortex_center}
\end{align}

\end_inset

From Archer 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Archer2008"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, if the vortex core maintains a Gaussian vorticity distribution, the core
 radius is approximately
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a^{2}=(R_{2}^{2}-R^{2})
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When a numerical model does not include the vortex formation process, the
 steady-state vortex-induced velocity field must instead be determined by
 first positing the vorticity distribution in the core.
 The simplest case, depicted in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Vortex-induced-velocity"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, is that of an infinitely thin core, with equivalent closed-form expressions
 for velocity taken either from the vortex streamfunction 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Nitsche1994"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 or from the Biot-Savart law 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Yoon2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Briefly,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
u_{r} & =\frac{\Gamma R}{4\pi}\frac{z-z_{c}}{B}(I_{1}-AI_{2})\\
u_{z} & =\frac{\Gamma R}{4\pi}\left(\left(R+r\frac{A}{B}\right)I_{2}-r\frac{I_{1}}{B}\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}=\frac{4}{\kappa}K(m)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{2}=\frac{4}{\kappa^{3}}\frac{E(m)}{1-m},$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $A=(z-z_{c})^{2}+r^{2}+R^{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B=-2rR$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa^{2}=(r+R)^{2}+(z-z_{c})^{2}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $m=\frac{4rR}{\kappa^{2}}$
\end_inset

