\begin_layout Standard
Existing literature on vortex generation from the open end of a shock tube
 lent credence to the basic concept 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Arakeri2004,Poudel2021,Murugan2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, but several operational constraints necessitated a novel design.
 Prior art generally involves discharge of air-formed vortex rings into
 the ambient atmosphere without shock interaction, while this research effort
 is fundamentally motivated by the study of mixing, which necessitates both
 an initial condition which is unmixed and a diagnostic technique which
 allows visualization of mixedness.
 Because of the dimensional limitations of the shock tube facility, the
 size of the vortex generator was constricted both by the limited vertical
 space between the end-wall of the shock tube and the concrete floor, as
 well as the desire to avoid wall effects in a 25 cm square cross section.
 Temporal uncertainty on the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm100$
\end_inset

