\begin_layout Chapter
Conclusions & future work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A vortex ring generator was designed to release a well-controlled vortex
 ring with a formation number of approximately 2.
 The generator allows seeding of the driven gas with acetone for laser-induced
 fluorescence, but a leak during experiments in the shock tube resulted
 in undesirable variations in the gas composition of the resultant vortex
 ring.
 Improvements in the vortex ring generator filling and operating procedure
 are necessary to prevent recurrence of this issue in future experiments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The particle image velocimetry data was likewise contaminated by weak image
 correlations due to a relatively large inter-frame timing of 50 
\begin_inset Formula $\si{\micro\second}$
\end_inset

.
 It may be possible to modify the pulse-burst laser to operate in a staggered-fr
ame output mode which would allow for smaller inter-pulse intervals of 10-20
 
\begin_inset Formula $\si{\micro\second}$
\end_inset

, but this remains to be seen.
 If such modification is not possible, further experiments will rely on
 a conventional PIV imaging setup with a dual-cavity laser and a specialized
 framing camera.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2D simulations showed promising results for the inclusion of a stratified
 gas interface in the vortex-shock interaction, with shock-deposited circulation
 close to theoretical predictions.
 These simulations neglect vortex stretching and are thus of limited predictive
 value when considering Widnall instability development, but 3D simulations
 at full resolution have a high computational cost.
 This cost might be mitigated to some degree by the use of adaptive mesh
 refinement.
 Additionally, the aliasing effects observed in 3D must be mitigated by
 careful choice of mesh topology and boundary conditions.
\end_layout

